lexUnit.name: squeal.v
lexUnit.definition: COD: to make or utter a long, high-pitched cry or noise

sentence.text: Eric was squealing louder than ever and pedalling the air with his legs .
The five Kenny children came crowding round like little goblins , dirty and ragged , but squealing happily .
They talked until the horses , squealing and nipping at each other , turned away to hurry purposefully across the field and stand afar , clouds of their breath plumed against the winter air .
Once , a dog squealed and went on squealing in pain , and a flying plank , grazing her shoulder , reminded her of what a high wind could do .
Tolby squealed and jerked away .
After a second Bert squealed and Ernie released him .
Brakes squealed and car horns blasted indignantly .
Dench 's guitar has become as prominent as his hooter , squealing and squalling throughout .
He squealed and rolled over in the sand , kicking frantically , as a rabbit does in a snare .
It squealed and struggled from her grip .
A hog in a headscarf squealed as she cleaved its skull with her axe .

Across the water , the loud hailers were blaring and squealing as they had in the winter , when Tzani-bey had caught and herded the Order .
In a scaly hollow a crowd of naked Perks fled squealing from the echo of their bounding feet .
Mollie squealed in delight .
As they scatter , squealing with alarm , the whale seizes a struggling pup in its jaws .
